It allows developers to create dynamic image carousels, supporting functionalities such as navigating through images, displaying metadata, and enhancing the user experience with modals for viewing images in full-screen mode.

####1. Define a Parent Element

Define a parent element where the images will be rendered. Ensure the element includes a `data-id` attribute for proper identification:

```html
<div id=\"myImages1\" data-id=\"myImages1\"></div>
```

####2. Draw An Image Series

Use the `imagesJs.draw` function to display a series of images. Provide an array of URLs to populate the image series dynamically:

```javascript
var parent = $('#myImages2');
imagesJs.draw(parent, {
    urls: [
        'https://example.com/image1.jpg',
        'https://example.com/image2.jpg',
        'https://example.com/image3.jpg'
    ]
});
```

This will render the images in the specified parent element.


####3. Support for Many Components

Use the `imagesJs.draw` function with another `parent` with a different id.

```javascript
var parent = $('#myImages2');
imagesJs.draw(parent, {
    urls: [
        'https://example.com/image5.jpg',
        'https://example.com/image6.jpg',
        'https://example.com/image7.jpg'
    ]
});
```

This will render a second images into the second parent element.

